	%% ============================================================
	%% Design Principles
	%% ============================================================

	%% 🔷 Core Modeling Principles
	%% 	1.	Each table has a single, well-defined responsibility
	%% Tables are designed to represent one concept only (e.g. configuration, input, result, workflow), avoiding mixed concerns.
	
	%% 	2.	Relationships reflect real business rules, not just foreign keys
	%% Cardinalities and optionality are chosen to express domain constraints, not merely technical implementation details.
	
	%% 	3.	Nullability is intentional and meaningful
	%% Nullable fields indicate valid domain states (e.g. optional associations, draft data), not incomplete design.

	%% ⸻

	%% 🔷 Configuration & Reference Data
	%% 	4.	Reference data is normalized and centralized
	%% Shared concepts (statuses, units, potentials) are defined once and reused across the system.
	
	%% 	5.	Volatile enums are modeled as tables, not database ENUMs
	%% Any value expected to evolve (statuses, workflows) is stored in catalog tables to avoid schema migrations.
	
	%% 	6.	Stable physical concepts may use ENUMs
	%% Concepts that are scientifically stable (e.g. usage mode) may use database ENUMs for safety and clarity.
	%% Note: unit magnitudes were originally an ENUM but were promoted to a `magnitude` table so country deployments can add custom magnitudes via seed/admin UI.

	%% ⸻

	%% 🔷 Methodology & Emission Factors
	
	%% 	7.	Methodology is versioned and country-scoped
	%% All categories, subcategories, and factors belong to a specific methodology version tied to a country.
	
	%% 	8.	Emission factors are defined by standardized dimensions, not free text
	%% User selections and factor matching are driven by normalized dimension values to ensure consistency and correctness.
	
	%% 	9.	Dimension cardinality reflects domain reality, not generic flexibility
	%% Emission factors support up to two dimensions by design, matching current methodology requirements and admin workflows.
	
	%% 	10.	Administrative workflows are hierarchical and sequential
	%% New entities are created top-down (category → subcategory → dimension → value → factor), enforcing consistency at each level.

	%% ⸻

	%% 🔷 Inventory & Calculation
	
	%% 	11.	Input, factor selection, and results are modeled as separate concerns
	%% User input, factor derivation, and calculated results are stored in distinct tables for clarity and auditability.
	
	%% 	12.	Results are always derived from immutable input snapshots
	%% Calculated emissions reference the exact input used, ensuring reproducibility even if inputs change later.
	
	%% 	13.	Historical data is preserved; updates create new versions
	%% Changes do not overwrite previous data but create new records, maintaining a complete audit trail.

	%% ⸻

	%% 🔷 Workflow & Submissions
	
	%% 	14.	Workflows are modeled as data, not booleans
	%% Submissions, approvals, and recognitions are represented explicitly rather than inferred from flags.
	
	%% 	15.	Polymorphism is handled via explicit subject tables
	%% Submissions reference a generic subject entity with concrete subtype tables, avoiding nullable polymorphic foreign keys.
	
	%% 	16.	Recognitions are awarded based on submissions, not raw entities
	%% This ensures all awards are traceable to a validated review process.

	%% ⸻

	%% 🔷 Audit & Governance
	
	%% 	17.	Audit fields are applied based on responsibility and mutability
	%% Operational tables are auditable; reference and system-owned tables may omit audit fields by design.
	
	%% 	18.	System-generated data does not pretend to have an author
	%% Automatically calculated results record timestamps but not created_by or updated_by.
	
	%% 	19.	Database constraints enforce correctness wherever possible
	%% Uniqueness, consistency, and invariants are enforced at the database level rather than relying solely on application logic.


	%% ⸻

	%% 🔷 Evolution & Maintainability
	
	%% 	20.	Design favors clarity and correctness over premature generalization
	%% Flexibility is introduced only when driven by real domain requirements, not hypothetical future use cases.
	
	%% 	21.	Future extensions are possible without breaking existing data
	%% The model anticipates evolution (e.g. new methodologies, new workflows) while keeping current usage simple and explicit.

	%% ⸻

	%% These principles are intentional. 
	%% Changes to the model should preserve these invariants unless there is a clear domain-driven reason to evolve them.

